8/6/2009 ASF
Looking into parse errors: 
- problem with object markers: tense-markers cannot take arguments with a morpheme in this slot. Tried reintroducing option:

    verb-slot3_input2_type=verb-slot2

It is not clear from the notes when and why this was removed. Grammatical example 40 is parsed now, so are ungrammatical examples with forbidden agreement combinations. As far as I can tell, this has not been looked into in detail yet (no attempt to exclude them through choices). Despite increased overgeneration, this seems an improvement since the ungrammatical examples were excluded for the wrong reasons before.
The other-features choices as explained above do not work, I'm not sure whether they worked before, and there is something missing in 'choices' or whether it only seemed to work, because the tense-marker could not take the second verb-slot.Maybe another solution where markers of different groups fall into different slots would work? E.g. slot for intransitive verbs and one for transitive verbs?
Similar idea might work to make sure that interaction between subj- and obj- markers work correctly.

Repair: verb-slot3_input1_type-verb-slot2

slot 3 should only take slot2, rather than either slot1 or 2. This removed spurious ambiguity, and all examples are still parsed. Only interaction 2nd and 1st person is still overgenerating.

LIGHT-VERBS: REPAIR1
Examples with light-verb were not parsing because nonfinite forms where considered 'non-inflected'. Added a morphological rule that creates nonfinite verbs. Possibly, other rules should make verbs 'finite' now (though this data test does not contain ungrammatical examples that are parsed because of this additional rule). 

LIGHT-VERBS: REPAIR2
Examples with light-verbs were still not parsing, because of case missmatch of subject. There are two possibilities: either auxiliary requires ergative case, in that case 'choices' should be adapted to aux-case, or there is a typo in the test-suite, and case should be "nom". Assumming test-suite was correct, I adapted choices.

8/9/2009 SS answers to questions from Antske

- example 23: is it ungrammatical because of the missing ya- or the missing -nri, or both?
It is ungrammatical because of the missing ya-

- example 29 and 22 are identical, which one should be different?

22 should have been different and not had the ergative suffix.  Intransitive verbs take nominative/absolutive subjects (basically the unmarked form).  Test suite changed to reflect this along with some more explanation in the comment .

- is example 30 supposed to be grammatical or ungrammatical, the description says ungrammatical, the judgment grammatical, could it be a copy-paste error: it is identical to example 21?
It should be ungrammatical (but isn't in the way it was written) the ergative marker "-rni" should have been deleted.  Test suite changed

- In 33 the verb is not recognized, should ngunya-ya-yu be ngunya-nya-yu?
The verb shouldn't be recognized here because the 3s marker "ya" should only appear if the coverbal root does not appear.  "Light verbs" such as "ju" either have a coverbal root that attaches to them or a lexical main verb that is separate from them.  If the coverbal root is not present, then the 3s marker cannot appear. If it is absent the 3s marker must appear.  Here it shouldn't appear, so I would expect the verb not to be recongnized.


- What are 48 and 50 supposed to look like: they contain suffixes that are not attached to anything, is this what they are testing?
In a way, it is supposed to be testing the ordering of the affixes.  Making sure that a suffix cannot appear as a prefix.  There was spacing error in 50 that fixed.

- Is example 49 testing the ordering of suffixes on the verb, or something else?
Yes this was testing the ordering of the affixes

- Is example 28 grammatical or ungrammatical? The description and judgment differ.
I think my understanding of the language changed and I changed the grammaticality judgement, but didn't change the comment.  So, the grammaticaly judgement is correct and the description is incorrect. 

I found the discussion of number and agreement to be confusing because I wanted "disagreement" to exist if number existed.  But after reading through the pages a few more times I finally decided that true syntactic disagreement doesn't exist for number.  Plural trumps singular and dual trumps plural as far the semantic representation goes, but the string is not ungrammatical when the pronoun and subject/object marker do not agree in number.

I changed the explanation in the test suite.

- example 29 and 22 more observations: What is the case in these examples supposed to be? The choices file and some descriptions (as well as gloss in example 29) suggest the subject should have nominative case: in the examples it bears an ergative, which case is correct? If example 22 is correct, 23 most likely is not (it has different case, but according to the description it is not testing for case).

The grammatical example (22) should have nominative/absolutive case for the subject and the ungrammatical one (29) should be ergative

- suffix "-mind" appears as "-mindi" in example 40 and 41, should this be "-mind" as well?
Yes.  The vowel can appear in different forms depeneding (I think) on the environment, but I meant to so the voweless form as the citation form for our purposes.

